@HIMITSU{{}}


@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{to}} (particle)" grammar="@HI{{to}} (particle)"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{to}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @FORMATION{{@N{{}} @HI{{@EM{{to}}}} ... }}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="list">@HI{{@EM{{to}}}}</a> follows nouns to indicate "and".
It can only be used with nouns and not phrases or clauses.
In this usage @HI{{@EM{{to}}}} follows each noun except the last.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{white}}iyuri@EM{{to}}@KJ{{red}}ibarano@KJ{{flower}}wo@KJ{{buy}}imashou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Let's buy some white lillies and red roses.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{to}}}} can be used to mark a comparison or contrast.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{ringo}}@EM{{to}}mikann@EM{{to}}dochiraga@KJ{{fond}}kidesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Which do you like better, apples or mandarin oranges.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="with">@HI{{@EM{{to}}}}</a> can mean "with" to indicate participants in an action.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{company^long}}ha @KJ{{section^long}}@EM{{to}}@KJ{{eat^matter}}woshiteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The company president is eating out with the division manager.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{to}}}} can indicate a change or a result.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^year}}ni@KJ{{sea^outside^trip^going^someone}}ha 1000@KJ{{ten*thousand^person}}@EM{{to}}natta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This year the number of overseas travellers reached ten million.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
Following an expression of quantity, @HI{{@EM{{to}}}} reinforces the negative idea of the sentence.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{mountain}}ni@KJ{{ascend}}runiha, 2@KJ{{time^interval}}@EM{{to}}kakarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It won't even take two hours to climb that mountain.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="quote">@HI{{@EM{{to}}}}</a> can indicate what someone says, asks or orders.
In this usage it acts as a quotation marker.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^book}}sanga, atode@KJ{{electricity^tale}}suru@EM{{to}}osshaimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yamamoto said that she would phone later.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="quote">@HI{{@EM{{to}}}}</a> can indicate what someone <a href="grammar-to-omou.html">thinks</a> or feels.
In this usage it acts as a quotation marker.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{come^year}}ha,@KT{{amerika}}he@KJ{{going}}kou@EM{{to}}@KJ{{consider}}eteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm thinking of going to the US next year.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
In the form <a href="grammar-to-iu.html">@HI{{@EM{{to}}}}@HI{{iu}}</a> it indicates the name of something
about which an explanation follows.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{generation^world}}@EM{{to}}iu@KJ{{miscellaneous^document}}wo@KJ{{know}}tteimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Do you know the magazine called <em>Sekai</em>?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{to}}}} follows an onomatopoeic adverb.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{star}}gakirakira@EM{{to}}@KJ{{radiance}}iteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The stars are twinkling.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{to}}}} indicates that a second action immediately follows a preceding one. In this usage, 
@HI{{sugu}} is often present too.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{morning^rouse}}kiru@EM{{to}}sugu, @KT{{ka-tenn}}wo@KJ{{open}}kemasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      As soon as I get up in the morning, I open the curtains.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="condition">@HI{{@EM{{to}}}}</a> can indicate the inevitability of a second action.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{car}}ga@KJ{{many}}kunaru@EM{{to}}@KJ{{mingle^traffic^thing^happenstance}}ga@KJ{{increase}}masu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      As the number of cars increases, more traffic accidents occur.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{to}}}} can indicate a hypothetical condition.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{bright^day}},@KJ{{heavens^spirit}}gaii@EM{{to}}@KJ{{plains^ball}}gadekimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      If the weather is good tomorrow we can play baseball.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{to}}}} can indicate that something has been learned as a result of an action.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mingle^turn}}de@KJ{{road-way}}wokiku@EM{{to}},sono@KJ{{meeting^company}}hasugu@KJ{{see}}tsukatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      After asking the way at a police box, I found the company straightaway.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{to}}}} follows two verbs in the volitional, or the same verb twice, the first time in the volitional and the second time in @HI{{mai}},
to indicate a lack of concern over which of two events occurs.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{he^woman}}ga@KJ{{one^person}}de@KT{{pa-texi-}}ni@KJ{{going}}kou@EM{{to}},
      @KJ{{going}}kumai@EM{{to}}, @KJ{{private}}hakamaimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I don't care whether she goes to the party alone or not.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When @HI{{@EM{{to}}}} follows a noun + @HI{{ga}} or noun + @HI{{wo}}, @HI{{@EM{{to}}}}
replaces those particles. For all other particles, @HI{{@EM{{to}}}} follows them rather than
replacing them.
</p>

<p>
The use of @HI{{@EM{{to}}}} as a conditional is described more fully <a href="grammar-to-conditional.html">here</a>.
</p>

